=====Usage notes=====
The meaning for “blue” and “black” is more commonly used in Classical Chinese, while in modern Chinese, the meaning for “green” is more common. In fact, 青 covered both  green and blue ("[[grue]]") until modern times. For example, {{zh-l|*青山綠水|hill or water green in color}}, {{zh-l|*青蘋果|green apple}}. However, there are still some expressions for the meaning of blue, e.g. {{zh-l|*青天|blue sky}}, {{zh-l|*青出於藍|blue comes from indigo; someone performing better than their teacher}}

In Cantonese, the use of {{lang|zh|青}} to mean “black” is still used in circumstances where to use {{zh-l|黑|hak1}} would be inauspicious, as it is a near-homophone of {{zh-l|乞|hat1|beggar}}. For example, {{zh-l|黑衣|hak1 ji1}} used to describe clothing would be a near-homophone of both beggar and a beggar's garment.

